│ The log shows the first transformation is foldIsPowerOf2 turning the select into icmp  │
│ eq %popcnt, 1. Alive2 demonstrates a counterexample with x=0: source yields false      │
│ safely because select bypasses the poison value, while target yields poison due to the │
│ unconditional use of the ctpop result carrying restrictive range metadata.             │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ foldIsPowerOf2 ignores the possibility that the ctpop value has range metadata that    │
│ excludes 0, which is only safe because of the original guard (x != 0). By removing the │
│ guard, the transform can introduce an unconditional use of a potentially               │
│ poison-producing value. InstCombine must ensure that the replacement is poison-safe.   │
│ Specifically, if the ctpop's range metadata does not include 0, the transform must not │
│ proceed, because the equality comparison will speculatively use ctpop even when x==0.  │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We need to add a safety check in foldIsPowerOf2 before constructing the unconditional  │
│ icmp against the ctpop result. If ctpop has range metadata that does not contain 0, we │
│ should bail out of the transform.                                                      │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit point 1 (lines 974-976 in                                                         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp): After retrieving CtPop in    │
│ the AND pattern, insert a check for range metadata including 0.                        │
│                                                                                        │
│ New code to insert between existing lines 974 and 976:                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│   // Do not speculatively use a potentially poison value. If CtPop carries             │
│   // range metadata that excludes 0, then removing the (X != 0) guard would            │
│   // make this use more poisonous when X == 0.                                         │
│   if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(CtPop))                                          │
│     if (MDNode *RangeMD = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {                     │
│       ConstantRange CR = getConstantRangeFromMetadata(*RangeMD);                       │
│       if (!CR.contains(APInt(CtPop->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(), 0)))              │
│         return nullptr;                                                                │
│     }                                                                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ This ensures we only fold when the ctpop value cannot become poison at 0.              │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit point 2 (lines 982-984 in                                                         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp): Apply the same check in the  │
│ OR pattern before creating the NE comparison, for symmetry and safety.                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ New code to insert between existing lines 982 and 984:                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│   // Do not speculatively use a potentially poison value. See comment above.           │
│   if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(CtPop))                                          │
│     if (MDNode *RangeMD = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {                     │
│       ConstantRange CR = getConstantRangeFromMetadata(*RangeMD);                       │
│       if (!CR.contains(APInt(CtPop->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth(), 0)))              │
