│ Notes:                                                                                 │
│ - This relies on getConstantRangeFromMetadata, which is available and already used     │
│ throughout LLVM.                                                                       │
│ - The APInt construction uses the bit-width of the ctpop result type.                  │
│ - We bail out of the fold if 0 is not included in the annotated range, preserving the  │
│ original poison-safe guarding.                                                         │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ The bug arises because foldIsPowerOf2 removes a guard and introduces an unconditional  │
│ use of a value with restrictive range metadata, potentially causing poison. By         │
│ guarding the transform with a check that ensures the ctpop value's range includes 0,   │
│ we maintain poison safety and avoid generating IR that is more poisonous than the      │
│ source. This fixes the miscompile reported by Alive2 in the provided reproducer        │
│ without affecting valid cases where the transformation is safe.                        │
